Now I see the real issue! Looking at the destructor on lines 45-73:

```cpp
template <class T>
CommBuffer<T>::~CommBuffer() {
#ifdef MPI_PARALLEL
  if (my_request_.use_count() == 1) { // This is the last shallow copy of this buffer
    // Make sure that there are no MPI requests still flying around associated
    // with this buffer before destroying it
    int flag;
    MPI_Status status;
    PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Test(my_request_.get(), &flag, &status));

    if (!flag) {
      if (*comm_type_ == BuffCommType::sender) {
        PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Wait(my_request_.get(), MPI_STATUS_IGNORE));  // <-- BLOCKING!
      } else {
        PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Cancel(my_request_.get()));
        PARTHENON_MPI_CHECK(MPI_Wait(my_request_.get(), MPI_STATUS_IGNORE));  // <-- BLOCKING!
      }
    }
  }
#endif
}
```

**The destructor calls MPI_Wait!** This is blocking - it waits for the MPI request to complete. When clearing the map, each CommBuffer's destructor is called, and if there are pending MPI operations, it **blocks waiting for them to complete**.

This explains everything:
1. When the map has many buffers with pending sends/receives
2. Each destructor calls `MPI_Wait` to ensure the request completes
3. If the remote end is slow or there's network congestion, this blocks
4. Clearing a map with 1000s of buffers means 1000s of potential MPI_Waits

This is a **serialized MPI synchronization bottleneck** hidden inside what looks like a simple map.clear(). 

Ranks with more communication channels—those handling more neighbor relationships during boundary exchange—will accumulate more buffers in the map and face more blocking waits during cleanup. I should check how many entries typically populate this map to understand the scale of the problem.

