content.text:
## Complete Explanation

The map `clear()` itself is fast - the expensive part is that **each `CommBuffer` destructor calls `MPI_Wait()`** to drain pending communication:

```cpp
// communication_buffer.cpp:45-74
~CommBuffer() {
  if (!flag) {  // Pending MPI request
    if (sender) {
      MPI_Wait(my_request);      // BLOCKS until send completes
    } else {
      MPI_Cancel(my_request);    // Cancel pending receive
      MPI_Wait(my_request);      // BLOCKS until cancel completes
    }
  }
}
```

**The math:**
- ~200 CommBuffers per rank (one per neighbor communication channel)
- Each `MPI_Wait` can block if the peer is slow
- 200 serialized blocking waits → 70-84ms total

**Why only some ranks:**
- Only ranks **receiving new mesh blocks** call `boundary_comm_map.clear()`
- They need to tear down old neighbor channels before setting up new ones
- Ranks keeping their blocks don't call Clear at all

Full analysis in `/users/ankushj/llm-thinkspace/20260116-claude/ANOMALY_ANALYSIS.md`

